# Building a High-Throughput Event Bus with Redis Streams

When developers need a message broker, they often default to **RabbitMQ** or **Apache Kafka**. While these are excellent, they introduce significant operational overhead. If you already have Redis in your stack, **Redis Streams** (introduced in Redis 5.0) provides an incredibly fast, persistent, and low-latency alternative.

## Why Redis Streams?
Unlike standard Redis Pub/Sub, Redis Streams are **durable and persistent** on disk. They also support **Consumer Groups**, allowing you to distribute workload across multiple worker nodes while keeping track of which consumer has acknowledged which message.

### Core Concept: Consumer Groups
Redis consumer groups partition incoming stream records so that each message goes to a single consumer in the group. It tracks:
1. **Last Delivered ID**: Keeps track of message history progress.
2. **Pending Entries List (PEL)**: Messages delivered but not yet acknowledged (`XACK`).

```bash
# Creating a consumer group in Redis
> XGROUP CREATE my_stream my_group $ MKSTREAM
```

## Implementation in Node.js
Below is a resilient implementation of a background worker consuming from a Redis Stream using the standard `ioredis` driver:

```typescript
import Redis from 'ioredis';

const redis = new Redis();
const STREAM_KEY = 'events:user_signup';
const GROUP_NAME = 'billing_processors';
const CONSUMER_ID = `worker_${process.pid}`;

async function startWorker() {
  while (true) {
    try {
      // Read messages that haven't been delivered to any consumer yet ('>')
      const response = await redis.xreadgroup(
        'GROUP', GROUP_NAME, CONSUMER_ID,
        'COUNT', '10',
        'BLOCK', '2000',
        'STREAMS', STREAM_KEY, '>'
      );

      if (!response) continue;

      const [_, messages] = response[0];
      for (const [msgId, fields] of messages) {
        const data = parseFields(fields);
        console.log(`Processing message ${msgId}:`, data);

        // Simulate billing setup
        await setupBilling(data.userId);

        // Acknowledge receipt
        await redis.xack(STREAM_KEY, GROUP_NAME, msgId);
      }
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Error processing stream message:', error);
      await sleep(1000); // Backoff
    }
  } 
}
```

## Conclusion
Redis Streams can easily push **100k+ operations per second** with sub-millisecond response times. For 90% of medium-to-large SaaS workloads, this eliminates the need for managing heavier messaging infrastructures while retaining transactional integrity.

# Advanced Change Detection and Zone.js Optimization in Angular

Angular is incredibly fast out of the box, but as application scale grows, you might notice lag in typing inputs, drag-and-drop triggers, or animations. Most of this performance degradation stems from **Zone.js** triggers initiating global Change Detection on minor browser events.

## The Core Problem: Zone.js Monkey Patching
Zone.js patches all standard asynchronous browser APIs (including `setTimeout`, `Promise.then`, `addEventListener`, and HTTP requests). Whenever any of these trigger, Zone.js tells Angular to scan the entire component tree from top to bottom checking for model updates.

In heavy real-time pages (like stock charts or canvases), a single mousemove event can trigger change detection 60 times a second, recalculating unrelated templates.

## Strategy 1: surgical `runOutsideAngular`
If you have a fast-firing event (e.g., listening to scroll positions or canvas drag), you must bypass Zone.js completely using `NgZone`:

```typescript
import { Component, OnInit, ElementRef, ViewChild, NgZone } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-canvas-painter',
  template: `<div #canvasContainer class="canvas-box"></div>` 
})
export class CanvasPainterComponent implements OnInit {
  @ViewChild('canvasContainer', { static: true }) canvasBox!: ElementRef;

  constructor(private ngZone: NgZone) {}

  ngOnInit() {
    // surgically bind event listener OUTSIDE of Angular's core digest
    this.ngZone.runOutsideAngular(() => {
      this.canvasBox.nativeElement.addEventListener('mousemove', (e: MouseEvent) => {
        this.drawOnScreen(e.clientX, e.clientY);
      });
    });
  }

  drawOnScreen(x: number, y: number) {
    // Performance-critical manipulation bypassing Angular bindings
    const box = this.canvasBox.nativeElement;
    box.style.transform = `translate3d(${x}px, ${y}px, 0)`;
  }
}
```

## Strategy 2: Default to `OnPush` Change Detection
By default, Angular uses the `ChangeDetectionStrategy.Default` strategy, which checks every component on every cycle. By switching to `ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush`, you tell Angular to **only** check this component and its children if:
- An `@Input()` reference changes.
- An event is fired directly from the component's template.
- You explicitly trigger detection using `ChangeDetectorRef.markForCheck()`.

```typescript
import { Component, ChangeDetectionStrategy } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-stats-row',
  templateUrl: './stats-row.component.html',
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush
})
export class StatsRowComponent {
  // Angular will not run expensive tree checks unless inputs change!
}
```

## Summary
By pairing `OnPush` components with selected `runOutsideAngular` loops, you can keep your main bundle footprint incredibly reactive and reach 60FPS on complex canvas interactions.

# Maximizing Email Deliverability: DKIM, SPF, and AWS SES Tuning

Sending an email is easy. Ensuring it actually lands in your recipient's **Inbox** rather than their **Spam/Promotions** folder is a science. Gmail and Yahoo introduced strict authentication requirements, making SPF, DKIM, and DMARC configuration non-negotiable for anyone sending mass or transactional mail.

## 1. The Trinity of DNS Authentication
To prove to receiving mail servers that you are who you say you are, you must configure three primary records in your DNS console:

### A. SPF (Sender Policy Framework)
SPF specifies which IP addresses are authorized to send email on behalf of your domain.

```text
# DNS TXT Record
Host: @
Value: v=spf1 include:amazonses.com ~all
```

### B. DKIM (DomainKeys Identified Mail)
DKIM adds a cryptographic signature to every email header. Receiving servers use your public DNS key to verify that the email body wasn't altered in transit.
AWS SES makes this easy by offering **Easy DKIM**, providing three CNAME records to publish.

### C. DMARC (Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting, and Conformance)
DMARC tells receiving servers what to do if an email fails SPF or DKIM checks. Start with a monitoring policy (`p=none`) and move to rejection (`p=reject`) once verified.

```text
# DNS TXT Record
Host: _dmarc.yourdomain.com
Value: v=DMARC1; p=quarantine; pct=100; rua=mailto:dmarc-reports@yourdomain.com
```

## 2. Setting Up an SES Bounce & Complaint Pipeline
AWS SES will suspend your sending capabilities if your **Bounce rate exceed 10%** or your **Complaint rate exceeds 0.1%**. You must actively handle these reports.

```
+---------+     Bounce/Complaint     +---------+     Trigger     +---------------+     Block Database
| AWS SES | -----------------------> | AWS SNS | --------------> | Lambda Worker | ------------------> User Account
+---------+                          +---------+                 +---------------+     (Suppress email)
```

### Resilient Lambda Consumer Example
We can route SNS bounce events to an AWS Lambda function which flags problematic accounts in our PostgreSQL DB:

```typescript
import { Handler } from 'aws-lambda';
import { Client } from 'pg';

export const handler: Handler = async (event) => {
  const client = new Client({ connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL });
  await client.connect();

  for (const record of event.Records) {
    const snsMessage = JSON.parse(record.Sns.Message);

    if (snsMessage.notificationType === 'Bounce') {
      const bounce = snsMessage.bounce;
      for (const recipient of bounce.bouncedRecipients) {
        console.warn(`Bounced Email Detected: ${recipient.emailAddress}`);
        // Flag email in DB to suppress future marketing attempts
        await client.query(
          'UPDATE users SET email_status = $1 WHERE email = $2',
          ['BOUNCED', recipient.emailAddress]
        );
      }
    }
  }

  await client.end();
  return { statusCode: 200 };
};
```

## Conclusion
Deliverability is built on **trust**. By combining secure cryptographic records with a real-time reactive feedback loop to suppress invalid or complaining emails, your domain reputation stays pristine, guaranteeing high placement across modern email providers.
